      "mainEntity": [
        { "@type": "Question", "name": "What is Online Reputation Management (ORM)?", "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Online Reputation Management (ORM) is the strategic practice of monitoring, influencing and improving how your business is perceived online — across Google search results, review platforms, social media, AI tools, news sites, Reddit and industry-specific directories. ORM covers proactive reputation building (generating positive reviews, creating authoritative content, building a strong Google SERP presence) and reactive reputation management (responding to negative reviews, suppressing harmful content, managing crisis situations). In 2026, ORM has expanded to include AI reputation — managing how ChatGPT, Gemini and Perplexity represent your brand to the 45% of consumers now using AI tools for business research." } },
        { "@type": "Question", "name": "How much does a bad online reputation cost a business?", "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "A damaged online reputation has direct, measurable financial consequences. 93% of consumers rely on online reviews before making a purchase decision — meaning your reviews are seen by almost every potential customer. 86% of prospective customers are deterred from buying when they see 1-2 star reviews, creating an immediate and ongoing revenue drain. Each additional star in a Yelp rating can increase revenue by up to 9%. Healthcare providers lose an average of $47,000 per negative review due to the high-stakes nature of patient decisions. Legal services lose $32,000 per negative review. Over 90% of individuals believe ORM directly influences at least 25% of a company's total market value. A single viral negative story can eliminate months or years of brand-building investment overnight." } },
        { "@type": "Question", "name": "How long does it take to repair a damaged reputation?", "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Reputation repair timelines depend on the severity of the damage, the volume of negative content and the competitiveness of your industry's search landscape. Review rating improvements typically become visible within 60 to 90 days of a systematic review generation programme. SERP reputation management — suppressing negative search results and building a positive Page 1 presence — typically takes 3 to 6 months for meaningful movement, with sustained improvement at 6 to 12 months. Crisis recovery, where a major negative event has occurred, requires both immediate damage control (15-30 minutes for initial response) and a sustained 6-12 month positive content rebuilding programme. Proactive ORM — starting before any crisis occurs — is always faster and cheaper than reactive repair." } },
        { "@type": "Question", "name": "What is AI Reputation Management and why does it matter in 2026?", "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "AI Reputation Management is the new frontier of ORM — monitoring and influencing how AI systems like ChatGPT, Gemini, Perplexity and Google AI Overviews represent your brand when users ask questions about your business, products or industry. In 2026, 45% of consumers use AI tools for business recommendations (up from just 6% in 2025). Critically, 85% of AI brand mentions come from third-party sources — not your own website. This means AI systems build their opinion of your brand primarily from reviews, news, social media and third-party content. If those sources are negative or absent, AI will either represent you poorly or not represent you at all — to nearly half of all potential buyers. Grow Boostly's ORM service includes full AI reputation monitoring and optimisation across all major AI platforms." } },
        { "@type": "Question", "name": "What is the difference between ORM and SEO?", "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "SEO (Search Engine Optimisation) focuses on improving the ranking of your own web pages for relevant keywords. ORM (Online Reputation Management) focuses on controlling what appears on Page 1 of Google when someone searches for your brand name — and ensuring it is positive, accurate and brand-controlled. ORM uses many of the same SEO techniques (content creation, link building, SERP strategy) but applies them specifically to brand name searches rather than keyword searches. ORM also extends beyond search engines to cover review platforms, social media, AI tools, news sites and industry directories — anywhere your brand reputation lives online." } },
